==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Heavy
<hw>Heav"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having the
heaves.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heavy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Heavy
<hw>Heav"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Heavier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Heaviest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>hevi</ets>, AS.
<ets>hefig</ets>, fr. <ets>hebban</ets> to lift, heave; akin to OHG.
<ets>hebig</ets>, <ets>hevig</ets>, Icel. <ets>h⟦oum⟧figr</ets>,
<ets>h⟦oum⟧fugr</ets>. See <er>Heave</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Heaved or lifted with labor; not light; weighty; ponderous; <as>as,
a <ex>heavy</ex> stone</as>; hence, sometimes, large in extent,
quantity, or effects; <as>as, a <ex>heavy</ex> fall of rain or snow; a
<ex>heavy</ex> failure; <ex>heavy</ex> business transactions, etc.</as>;
often implying strength; <as>as, a <ex>heavy</ex> barrier</as>; also,
difficult to move; <as>as, a <ex>heavy</ex> draught</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not easy to bear; burdensome; oppressive; hard to
endure or accomplish; hence, grievous, afflictive; <as>as,
<ex>heavy</ex> yokes, expenses, undertakings, trials, news,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hand of the Lord was <qex>heavy</qex> upon them of Ashdod.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Sam. v. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king himself hath a <qex>heavy</qex> reckoning to make.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sent hither to impart the <qex>heavy</qex> news.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Trust him not in matter of <qex>heavy</qex> consequence.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Laden with that which is weighty; encumbered;
burdened; bowed down, either with an actual burden, or with care, grief,
pain, disappointment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>heavy</qex> [sorrowing] nobles all in council were.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A light wife doth make a <qex>heavy</qex> husband.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Slow; sluggish; inactive; or lifeless, dull,
inanimate, stupid; <as>as, a <ex>heavy</ex> gait, looks, manners, style,
and the like; a <ex>heavy</ex> writer or book.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whilst the <qex>heavy</qex> plowman snores.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of a <qex>heavy</qex>, dull, degenerate mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither [is] his ear <qex>heavy</qex>, that it can not hear.</q>
<rj><qau>Is. lix. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Strong; violent; forcible; <as>as, a <ex>heavy</ex>
sea, storm, cannonade, and the like</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Loud; deep; -- said of sound; <as>as, <ex>heavy</ex>
thunder</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But, hark! that <qex>heavy</qex> sound breaks in once more.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Dark with clouds, or ready to rain; gloomy; -- said
of the sky.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Impeding motion; cloggy; clayey; -- said of earth;
<as>as, a <ex>heavy</ex> road, soil, and the like</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Not raised or made light; <as>as, <ex>heavy</ex>
bread</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Not agreeable to, or suitable for, the stomach; not
easily digested; -- said of food.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>Having much body or strength; -- said of wines, or
other liquors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>With child; pregnant.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Heavy artillery</b></col>. <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>Guns of great weight or large caliber, esp. siege, garrison, and
seacoast guns.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Troops which serve heavy guns.</cd>
-- <col><b>Heavy cavalry</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Cavalry</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Heavy fire</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a continuous or
destructive cannonading, or discharge of small arms.</cd> --
<col><b>Heavy metal</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>large guns carrying
balls of a large size; also, large balls for such guns.</cd><-- a type
of rock music (1970's), with a hard beat, amplified electronically -->
-- <col><b>Heavy metals</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Metal</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Heavy weight</b></col>, <cd>in
wrestling, boxing, etc., a term applied to the heaviest of the classes
into which contestants are divided. Cf. <cref>Feather weight</cref>
<sd>(c)</sd>, under <er>Feather</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Heavy</xex> is used in composition to form many
words which need no special explanation; as, <xex>heavy</xex>-built,
<xex>heavy</xex>-browed, <xex>heavy</xex>-gaited, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heavy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Heavy
<hw>Heav"y</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Heavily; -- sometimes used in
composition; <as>as, <ex>heavy</ex>-laden</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heavy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Heavy
<hw>Heav"y</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make heavy.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heavy-armed</ent>⟦br⟧
